<div class="faq-sec" data-category="vlan">
  <h3><span class="ico"><i class="bi bi-tags"></i></span> Per-User VLAN Authentication (BSNL-style)</h3>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">What is per-user VLAN auth and why use it? <i class="bi bi-chevron-down chev"></i></div>
    <div class="faq-a">
      <p>It's the same authentication model that <strong>BSNL FTTH and Jio AirFiber</strong> use. Each customer's ONU port tags every outgoing frame with a dedicated <strong>CVID</strong> (customer VLAN id). The MikroTik BNG only accepts that user's PPPoE login if the incoming VLAN tag matches the VLAN we assigned to them.</p>
      <p><strong>Even if someone leaks the PPPoE password</strong>, they cannot dial from a different ONU because their frames would carry a different VLAN tag and the BNG will reject the session.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">How do I prepare the MikroTik trunk port? (manual prep, do this ONCE) <i class="bi bi-chevron-down chev"></i></div>
    <div class="faq-a">
      <p>You only need to prep one physical port — the port that receives Q-tagged frames from your OLT (usually <code>ether2</code> or a dedicated uplink).</p>

      <h5>STEP 1 — Pick the right port</h5>
      <p>Identify the MikroTik port that's plugged into your OLT uplink. This will become the "VLAN trunk".</p>

      <h5>STEP 2 — Make sure tags survive on this port</h5>
      <p>The trunk port must NOT be part of any bridge that strips VLAN tags. Either:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Keep it un-bridged</strong> (simplest). The PPPoE server binds directly to <code>ether2</code> + the auto-created <code>vlan-N</code> sub-interfaces.</li>
        <li><strong>OR</strong> put it in a bridge with <code>vlan-filtering=yes</code> set on the bridge.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Winbox / Terminal example (un-bridged path — recommended):</strong></p>
      <p><code>/interface ethernet set ether2 disabled=no comment="OLT-trunk"</code></p>
      <p>Then make sure <code>ether2</code> does <strong>not</strong> appear under <code>/interface bridge port</code>. If it does, remove it:</p>
      <p><code>/interface bridge port remove [find interface=ether2]</code></p>

      <h5>STEP 3 — That's it. Hit "VLAN (1-click)" in the SuperAdmin NAS console</h5>
      <p>From SuperAdmin → Admin Management → NAS Console, click <strong>VLAN (1-click)</strong> on the NAS row. Pick your range (e.g. <code>100-999</code>), the trunk interface, the PPPoE service-name, and click <strong>Push to router</strong>. The platform will:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Seed VLAN pool rows in the database</li>
        <li>Create one <code>vlan-N</code> sub-interface per VID on your trunk port</li>
        <li>Switch the PPPoE Server to <code>use-radius=yes</code></li>
        <li>Enable <code>/ppp aaa use-radius=yes</code></li>
        <li>Enable <code>/radius incoming accept=yes</code></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">How does this work on the OLT side? Do I need to do anything there? <i class="bi bi-chevron-down chev"></i></div>
    <div class="faq-a">
      <p>Yes. The OLT is what stamps the CVID on each user's traffic — the MikroTik just verifies it. You must:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Configure each ONU's UNI port with the assigned CVID (the VLAN you allocated to the user inside the platform).</li>
        <li>Trunk all CVIDs upstream to the MikroTik (1:1 transparent VLAN translation — same VID end-to-end). This is the BSNL pattern.</li>
        <li>Make sure your OLT's PON uplink is in trunk mode tagged for the VLAN range you seeded.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Specifics depend on your OLT vendor (BDCOM, V-SOL, Huawei, ZTE, Vsol, etc.). Search your OLT docs for "<strong>per-ONU VLAN translation</strong>" or "<strong>CVID per UNI</strong>".</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">How do I assign a VLAN to a customer? <i class="bi bi-chevron-down chev"></i></div>
    <div class="faq-a">
      <p>Open <strong>Add User</strong> (or the Edit User popup on an existing customer). Tick the <strong>VLAN Enable</strong> checkbox and pick a VLAN ID from the dropdown (auto-populated with FREE VLANs from your pool).</p>
      <p>The platform's background worker (<code>vlan-radius-sync</code>) then writes <code>Tunnel-Type</code>, <code>Tunnel-Medium-Type</code> and <code>Tunnel-Private-Group-Id</code> into FreeRADIUS within 30 seconds. The user's next PPPoE dial-in will be enforced against that VLAN.</p>
      <p><strong>Existing customers without the VLAN toggle are NOT affected</strong> — they keep dialing in over PPPoE exactly as before.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">How do I view, edit, release, or remove existing VLANs? <i class="bi bi-chevron-down chev"></i></div>
    <div class="faq-a">
      <p>From SuperAdmin → NAS Console, click <strong>Manage VLANs</strong> on the NAS row. You get a table with every VLAN in the pool plus action buttons per row:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Release</strong> — frees the VLAN from its current customer (customer keeps PPPoE but loses VLAN enforcement)</li>
        <li><strong>Mark Free / Reserve</strong> — change pool state</li>
        <li><strong>Push to router</strong> — re-create the <code>vlan-N</code> interface on MikroTik if it was deleted</li>
        <li><strong>Remove from router</strong> — delete only the <code>vlan-N</code> interface from MikroTik (pool row stays)</li>
        <li><strong>Retire</strong> — hide from future dropdowns but keep for history</li>
        <li><strong>🗑️ (red)</strong> — hard-delete from the pool permanently</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">What if I want to ADD more VLANs to an existing pool? <i class="bi bi-chevron-down chev"></i></div>
    <div class="faq-a">
      <p>Click <strong>VLAN (1-click)</strong> again with a non-overlapping range (e.g. 1000-1500). The platform skips any VID that already exists in the pool and only adds the new ones. The MikroTik interfaces are also idempotent — duplicates are silently skipped.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">How do I verify a VLAN binding is actually catching a wrong login? <i class="bi bi-chevron-down chev"></i></div>
    <div class="faq-a">
      <p>On the MikroTik, open <strong>Log</strong> and watch when the user dials in. With <code>use-radius=yes</code> active, a mismatched VLAN will produce an entry like:</p>
      <p><code>pppoe,error,info: &lt;username&gt; logged out, RADIUS attr Tunnel-Private-Group-Id mismatch</code></p>
      <p>If you see "authenticated" then the user's incoming Q-tag matched the VLAN we expected.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">Does this work with my existing PPPoE, Hotspot or Static-IP customers? <i class="bi bi-chevron-down chev"></i></div>
    <div class="faq-a">
      <p><strong>Yes — completely additive.</strong> All existing customers stay on the legacy path until you explicitly enable the VLAN toggle on each one. Hotspot and Static-IP users are skipped by the sync worker (only PPPoE users participate in VLAN auth — that's BSNL's design too).</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

